```php
function total($arr) {
  $s = 0;
  foreach ($arr as $n) { $s += $n; }
  return $s;
}
echo total([1, 2, 3]);
```

```php
function classer($notes) {
  foreach ($notes as $n) {
    echo $n >= 10 ? "admis " : "recale ";
  }
}
classer([15, 8]);
```

```php
class Robot {
  public $nom;
  function __construct($n) { $this->nom = $n; }
  function saluer() { return "Je suis " . $this->nom; }
}
$r = new Robot("R-7");
echo $r->saluer();
```

```php
function moyenne($d) { return array_sum($d) / count($d); }
echo moyenne(["a" => 10, "b" => 20]);
```

Un vrai script combine tableau, boucle et condition :

```php
<?php
$liste = ["a", "b", "a"];
$count = 0;
foreach ($liste as $x) {
    if ($x == "a") { $count++; }
}
echo "Total : $count\n";
```

En ligne de commande, un script PHP reçoit ses arguments via `$argv` : `$argv[1]` est le premier.

```php
<?php
function saluer($x) {
    echo "Bonjour $x\n";
}
saluer($argv[1]);
```

Lancé avec l'argument `Monde`, il affiche : `Bonjour Monde`.
